<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: FA8072"><a class="external text" href="../../w/index-title=Portal_Lutheranism_Selected_article_2&action=edit.php.html"><span style="color: FA8072">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>
<h2 style="font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:FA8072;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_article">Selected article</span></h2>
</div>
<div style="border: 1px solid #aaaaaa; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #EEE8AA;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">
<div style="float:left;margin-right:1em"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Philipp_Jacob_Spener.jpg" class="image" title="Philipp Jacob Spener, the &quot;Father of Pietism&quot;."><img alt="Philipp Jacob Spener, the &quot;Father of Pietism&quot;." src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7e/Philipp_Jacob_Spener.jpg/150px-Philipp_Jacob_Spener.jpg" width="150" height="187" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7e/Philipp_Jacob_Spener.jpg/225px-Philipp_Jacob_Spener.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7e/Philipp_Jacob_Spener.jpg/300px-Philipp_Jacob_Spener.jpg 2x" /></a></div>
<b>Pietism</b> was a movement within <a href="Lutheranism" title="Lutheranism">Lutheranism</a>, lasting from the late 17th century to the mid 18th century and later. It proved to be very influential throughout <a href="Protestantism" title="Protestantism">Protestantism</a> and <a href="Anabaptist" title="Anabaptist">Anabaptism</a>, inspiring not only <a href="Anglicanism" title="Anglicanism">Anglican</a> priest <a href="John_Wesley" title="John Wesley">John Wesley</a> to begin the <a href="Methodism" title="Methodism">Methodist movement</a>, but also <a href="Alexander_Mack" title="Alexander Mack">Alexander Mack</a> to begin the <a href="Schwarzenau_Brethren" title="Schwarzenau Brethren">Brethren</a> movement. The Pietist movement combined the Lutheranism of the time with the <a href="Calvinism" title="Calvinism">Reformed</a>, and especially <a href="Puritan" title="Puritan">Puritan</a>, emphasis on individual <a href="Piety" title="Piety">piety</a>, and a vigorous <a href="Christianity" title="Christianity">Christian</a> life.
<table class="noprint" width="100%" border="0" style="padding: 0; margin: 0; background-color:transparent">
<tr>
<td>
<div style="text-align:right;margin-right:10px;margin-bottom:4px;">
<p><b><a href="Pietism" title="Pietism">Read more...</a></b></p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<div style="clear:both;"></div>
</div>
<div style="clear: both; border: solid #aaaaaa; border-width: 1px 1px 0; background: #87CEEB; color: FA8072; padding: .1em;padding-top: .1em;padding-left: .1em;padding-right: .1em;padding-bottom: .1em;text-align: center;font-family: sans-serif;font-size:100%;margin-bottom: 0px;">
<div class="plainlinks" style="float:right;margin-bottom:.1em;font-size:80%; color: FA8072"><a class="external text" href="../../w/index-title=Portal_Lutheranism_Selected_biography_2&action=edit.php.html"><span style="color: FA8072">edit</span></a>&#160;&#160;</div>
<h2 style="font-size:100%; font-weight:bold; border: none; margin: 0; padding:0; padding-bottom:.1em; color:FA8072;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_biography">Selected biography</span></h2>
</div>
<div style="border: 1px solid #aaaaaa; border-top-width: 1px; vertical-align: top;background: #EEE8AA;opacity: 1; color: black; text-align: left; margin: 0 0 10px; padding: 1em;padding-top: .3em;">
<div style="float:left;margin-right:1em"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Johann_Sebastian_Bach.jpg" class="image" title="Portrait of Johann Sebastian Bach"><img alt="Portrait of Johann Sebastian Bach" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Johann_Sebastian_Bach.jpg/150px-Johann_Sebastian_Bach.jpg" width="150" height="185" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Johann_Sebastian_Bach.jpg/225px-Johann_Sebastian_Bach.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Johann_Sebastian_Bach.jpg/300px-Johann_Sebastian_Bach.jpg 2x" /></a></div>
<b>Johann Sebastian Bach</b> was a <a href="Germany" title="Germany">German</a> <a href="Composer" title="Composer">composer</a> and <a href="Organ_(music)" title="Organ (music)">organist</a> whose sacred and secular works for choir, orchestra, and solo instruments drew together the strands of the <a href="Baroque_music" title="Baroque music">Baroque</a> period and brought it to its ultimate maturity. Although he introduced no new forms, he enriched the prevailing German style with a robust <a href="Counterpoint" title="Counterpoint">contrapuntal</a> technique, an unrivalled control of harmonic and motivic organisation in composition for diverse musical forces, and the adaptation of rhythms and textures from abroad, particularly Italy and France. His works are revered for their intellectual depth and technical and artistic beauty. While Bach's fame as an organist was great during his lifetime, he was not particularly well-known as a composer. His adherence to Baroque forms and <a href="Contrapuntal" title="Contrapuntal" class="mw-redirect">contrapuntal</a> style was considered "old-fashioned" by his contemporaries, especially late in his career when the musical fashion tended towards <a href="Rococo#Music" title="Rococo">Rococo</a> and later <a href="Classical_period_(music)" title="Classical period (music)">Classical</a> styles. A revival of interest and performances of his music began early in the 19th century, and he is now widely considered to be one of the greatest composers in the Western tradition.
<table class="noprint" width="100%" border="0" style="padding: 0; margin: 0; background-color:transparent">
<tr>
<td>
<div style="text-align:right;margin-right:10px;margin-bottom:4px;">
<p><b><a href="Johann_Sebastian_Bach" title="Johann Sebastian Bach">Read more...</a></b></p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
